[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Met}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Met</span></span></span></span></span> be the category of metric spaces and nonexpansive maps. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>F</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{F}: \\mathbf{Met} \\to \\mathbf{Met}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9468em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9468em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2523em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.1667em;\"><span class=\"mord\">^</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Met</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Met</span></span></span></span></span> is a functor lifting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F:\\mathbf{Set} \\to \\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> preserves monomorphisms (i.e. injections), does <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>F</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{F}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9468em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9468em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2523em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.1667em;\"><span class=\"mord\">^</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> preserve isometries ?</p>\n<p>I haven't been able to prove this nor find a counterexample so I am looking for help.</p>",
        "id": 268577276,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642614353
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aren't isometries isomorphisms?</p>",
        "id": 268582443,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642616610
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think some authors assume isometries are bijection, for me they are only distance preserving maps (they are automatically injective).</p>",
        "id": 268582649,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642616694
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay. When you say \"lifting <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F:\\mathbf{Set} \\to \\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>\", do you mean lifting along the forgetful/underlying set functor?</p>",
        "id": 268583393,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642617024
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes!</p>",
        "id": 268583423,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642617042
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Given an isometry <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:X \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> which is not an isomorphism, could we have some silly lifting of the identity functor which is the identity almost everywhere on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Met}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Met</span></span></span></span></span> except that spaces under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> have their distance function multiplied by a factor of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1 - \\epsilon</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 268584089,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642617381
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry, one last precision, I am working with metric spaces with distance bounded by 1, or equivalently extended metric spaces.</p>\n<p>In your example, the coprojection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>↪</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>+</mo><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y \\hookrightarrow Y + \\mathbf{1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">1</span></span></span></span> (coproducts put any two elements in disjoint parts at distance <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span> in the extended case) is not nonexpansive after doing the liting.</p>",
        "id": 268584797,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642617700
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No no, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> is also reduced in distance (it's under itself with the identity morphism)</p>",
        "id": 268584960,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642617778
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>+</mo><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y+\\mathbf{1}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">1</span></span></span></span> is not reduced right?</p>",
        "id": 268585017,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642617814
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Huh? You've just given a morphism from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> to it, so it would be</p>",
        "id": 268585124,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642617868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh I didn't understand spaces under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> like that, so it is any space with a morphism from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> to it ?</p>",
        "id": 268585263,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642617940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes :D</p>",
        "id": 268585348,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642617972
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I don't know if my idea actually works, but I don't think you've broken it yet)</p>",
        "id": 268585418,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642618005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, but I feel like your example does work <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 268585487,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642618033
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks</p>",
        "id": 268585502,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1642618040
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(it doesn't work because there are morphisms between every pair of non-empty metric spaces!!)</p>",
        "id": 268585536,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642618058
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But hopefully it at least illustrates why isometries <em>could</em> fail to be preserved?</p>",
        "id": 268585643,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1642618093
    }
]